posts.name: fovea1959
posts.cooked:
We’re having our first experience with PathPlanner, and it’s not going well.

Our first test is to just have it drive one meter in a straight line. It goes over 4 meters.

Our odometry is accurate; we confirmed that by looking at the values that YAGSL puts in SmartDashboard, and the PathPlanner GUI shows accurately the path that the robot is following (which is not at all what is on the screen for what we requested).

Where do we start looking?

Are you using PathPlannerAuto instead of PathFollowing?

Aside from that and using an Auto instead of Path make sure that the alliance is false. Also reduce your module speed to the physical limit of your module ideally (or just keep it lower but mjansen4857 doesnt like that )

Then if driving with chassis speed that just spins positively doesn’t spin CCW+ you would need to follow the 8 steps.

posts.name: Greg
posts.cooked:
We have definitely set the Drive Station to Blue Alliance, and PathPlanner shows the robot in the correct starting location.

Our code is here: GitHub - FRC3620/FRC3620_2024_Maestro at test-yagsl-controller

I thought that potentially the problem was with the driveConversionFactor, but since odometry is correct (we’ve driven the robot one meter and watched the Pose2d update by 1 meter), I think the driveConversionFactor has to be right…

Additionally, we’ve tried to slow the robot way down by changing the maximumSpeed in the SwerveSubsystem. When we look on the simulator, the robot is very slow, but on the field, it is still very fast.
how about your angle motor and drive motor conversion factors? We were experiencing a similar issue to yours, and when we fixed our conversion factors, our PathPlanner auto worked.

posts.name: Greg
posts.cooked:
I think our conversion factors are correct. We are using custom swerve modules, so the defaults presented by YAGSL don’t apply, but to test our conversion factors, we did the following:

We used the existing tape on the field (centerline to Blue Wing Line) which happens to be 8’ apart. We then drove the robot (in teleop) from the centerline to the Blue Wing Line and measured the change in getPose().getX(). We expected the X component of the Pose to change by ~2.4m, which it did.

We also used the field layout component of FRC Web Components and drove the robot around in Teleop mode. When watching the robot drive on the field, it’s position (and rotation) in FRC Web Components was accurately measured.  Based on this information, we believe the DriveConversionFactor and AngleConversionFactor are correct.

There is one weird issue around conversion factors, however.

We are specifying our conversion factor in the physicalproperties.json file in the YAGSL configuration directory.

In the SwerveSubsystem Constructor , however, driveConversionFactor appears to be calculated and returned a different value from our config directory:

We’ve tried changing this value as well, but it didn’t seem to make a difference.

posts.name: Jason Daming
posts.cooked:
Your Holonomic Pathfollower PID is very low, have you tried this at normal values (~5)?

Does the back auto do the same overshoot?

posts.name: Greg
posts.cooked:
Changing the Pathfollower PID made a huge impact. I think that “5” was way too high (the robot just violently oscillated back and forth). Our current (translational) PID is set to “1”:

With this config, (and a PathPlanner max speed of 0.5m/s) robot translation is almost correct – the robot consistently drives about 4-6" too far, then comes back. The final position is correct, but the robot always overshoots and comes back.

When we tried to increase the speed, the path following got less accurate (much more oscillation along a short (2m) path) and still overshot by 4-6".

Do you have any suggestions for tuning the path follower PID to get it to be more consistent?

Thanks in advance for all your help!

I don’t know if this will fix it, but I suggest remaking the path. As in delete the old one and remake it. This has fixed issues I have had with PathPlanner. I’m going to list the issues that it has helped with:

instead of following the planned path which was to drive forward a meter or so and then just drive back, the robot had a mind of its own going at like 50% speed at a 45 degree angle from where it was supposed to go and just kept going until I disabled.

instead of following the planned path which was to drive forward a meter or so and then just drive back, the robot had a mind of its own going at like 50% speed at a 45 degree angle from where it was supposed to go and just kept going until I disabled.

(this one is not related to the issue you are having but is just an example in case this happens for you) any time I tried to add a waypoint or drag one of the waypoints already on screen, the application closed itself out. deleting the path and remaking seems to fix this issue.

posts.name: fovea1959
posts.cooked:
Problem solved.

The maximum robot speed that we provide in code when created the YAGSL SwerveDrive was too low by an order of magnitude (0.4 instead of 4).

Thanks to all who helped us with this! It’s our first experience with Pathplanner, lots of learning!

accepted_answer.excerpt:
Problem solved. 
The maximum robot speed that we provide in code when created the YAGSL SwerveDrive was too low by an order of magnitude (0.4 instead of 4). 
Thanks to all who helped us with this! It’s our first experience with Pathplanner, lots of learning!
